{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505708"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2468"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2468"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.4,0.13,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85663"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2468"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69957"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1818"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42498"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43161"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85663"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of raised, red bumps on her shins. She has never had anything like this before. Over the last six months, she has been feeling generally lethargic and run down, with occasional episodes of shortness of breath on exertion. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Multiple painful, erythematous, subcutaneous nodules are clearly visible on both shins, ranging in size from 1-3 cm. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. Routine blood tests performed six months ago were normal apart from a corrected serum calcium of 2.90 mmol/L (2.10-2.60).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colonoscopy","Serum angiotensin converting enzyme","Chest X-ray","Biopsy of a skin nodule","Serum p-ANCA and c-ANCA"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with erythema nodosum, respiratory symptoms, and hypercalcaemia, which strongly suggests sarcoidosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation as it may reveal bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, which is characteristic of sarcoidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum angiotensin converting enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E levels may be elevated in sarcoidosis but have poor sensitivity and specificity. This test would not be the first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiopsy of a skin nodule\u003C/strong\u003E is usually unnecessary for erythema nodosum as the diagnosis is typically clinical. Moreover, the underlying cause needs to be identified first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if inflammatory bowel disease was suspected, but the combination of symptoms and hypercalcaemia makes sarcoidosis more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum p-ANCA and c-ANCA\u003C/strong\u003E are used to investigate vasculitis, which is a less likely diagnosis given the presentation and would not explain the hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe causes of erythema nodosum are varied and in up to 50% there is no identifiable cause. Recognised causes include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfection (most commonly identified cause, common infections include Streptococcus, Tuberculosis and \u003Cem\u003EYersinia sp.\u003C/em\u003E among others, while viral causes include HIV, parvovirus B19, hepatitis B and C, and Epstein-Barr Virus)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedications (sulfonamides, aspirin, penicillin, methimazole, azathioprine, sorafenib, phenytoin, valproate, lenalidomide, bromides, and iodides)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESarcoidosis (10-25% of erythema nodosum in young women)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPregnancy (2% of women develop erythema nodosum, usually during the second trimester)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInflammatory bowel disease (seen in 4-15% of patients with Crohn\u0027s disease)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParaneoplastic disease (reports of erythema nodosum occurring with lymphoma have been published)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAutoimmune disease (may be a sign of systemic autoimmune disease such as hepatitis, lupus, vasculitis, rheumatoid arthritis and others)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosis of erythema nodosum is primarily clinical, however basic laboratory and radiographic testing may help support the diagnosis. Testing may include complete blood examination and electrolytes, as well as anti-Streptolysin O antibodies, throat culture, C-reactive protein and a chest radiograph. Biopsy of the lesion is usually not necessary but may be considered if the lesions are atypical.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema nodosum with respiratory symptoms and hypercalcaemia is highly suggestive of sarcoidosis.","Chest X-ray is the appropriate first-line investigation for suspected sarcoidosis, which may reveal bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy."],"references":["Chowaniec M, Starba A, Wiland P. Erythema nodosum - review of the literature. Reumatologia. 2016;54(2):79-82. doi: 10.5114/reum.2016.60217. Epub 2016 Jun 3. PMID: 27407284; PMCID: PMC4918048. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27407284/","Leung AKC, Leong KF, Lam JM. Erythema nodosum. World J Pediatr. 2018 Dec;14(6):548-554. doi: 10.1007/s12519-018-0191-1. Epub 2018 Sep 29. PMID: 30269303. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30269303/","Marcoval J, Moreno A, Ma\u00f1\u00e1 J. Papular sarcoidosis of the knees: a clue for the diagnosis of erythema nodosum-associated sarcoidosis. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2003 Jul;49(1):75-8. doi: 10.1067/mjd.2003.490. PMID: 12833012. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12833012/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69957"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2468"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69957"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-17T11:43:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-17T11:43:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2468"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85663"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":